{{Refimprove|date=May 2016}}
{{Jainism}}
'''''Panch Kalyanaka Pratishtha Mahotsava'''''  is a traditional [[Jain]] ceremony that consecrates one or more Jain [[Tirthankara]] [[icon]]s with celebration of [[Panch Kalyanaka]] (five auspicious events). The ceremony is generally held when new Jain temple is erected or new idols are installed in temples.{{sfn|Jaini|1998|p=}}

==Panch Kalyanaka==
[[File:Gajrath,_Tada,_Feb_9_2017,_from_Ahinsa_TV.jpg|thumb|right|Gajrath chariot in Tada, Bundelkhand]]
{{Main|Panch Kalyanaka}}
The five kalyanakas are the five major events associated with a [[Tirthankara]] are:{{sfn|Jaini|1998|p=}}

# Chyavan (conception)
# Janma (birth)
# Diksha (renounciation)
# Keval Gyan (omniscience)
# Moksha (liberation)

These events are celebrated in relation to icons of [[Tirthankara]]s which is called ''Pratishtha''. After the pratishtha the statue represents the [[Tirthankara]], and becomes a worshippable object.

A pratishtha must be authorised by an acknowledged leader of the sangha, an [[Acharya]] or a [[Bhattaraka]], or a representative (pratishthacharya), who can recite the sacred suri-mantra to mark the final step in the installation ceremony. The [[Shvetambara]] sect requires a ceremony called anjana-shalaka. Once an idol is fully installed, it must be worshipped daily.{{sfn|Jaini|1998|p=}}

The [[Bhattaraka]] Devendrakeerti of [[Humbaj]] is the only Bhattaraka who has participated in the installations in overseas countries including USA, Canada and Australia.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}

In [[Jainism in Bundelkhand|Bundelkhand]] region, a panch-kalyanak pratishtha is accompanied by a [[Gajrath|gaj rath]] (chariot drawan by elephants) procession.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Id7_qEjcgv4  SESAI PANCH KALYANAK MAHOTSAV GAGRATH FERI 22-04-2017, Toofan tv Damoh, Apr 23, 2017]</ref>

