[[Category:Jain behaviour and experience]]

[[Image:Kanamara Matsuri 2007 (phallus festival)-crop.jpg|thumb|right|225px|A modern gathering in Japan ([[Kanamara Matsuri]]) similar to those of the Greek tradition.]] '''Phallic processions''', or '''Penis Parade''',<ref name="Younger">Tim Younger [http://www.kingmixers.com/TimonClouds.html THE PENIS PARADE or A TALE OF A TAIL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622173539/http://www.kingmixers.com/TimonClouds.html |date=2008-06-22 }}</ref> called ''phallika'' in [[ancient Greece]], were a common feature of [[Dionysiac celebrations]]; they were [[procession]]s that advanced to a cult center, and were characterized by [[obscenities]] and [[verbal abuse]].<ref name="Dunkle">[http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/classics/links.html Dunkle, Roger] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822065038/http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/classics/links.html |date=2007-08-22 }} ''[http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/classics/dunkle/comedy/komos.htm The origins of comedy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324082204/http://depthome.brooklyn.cuny.edu/classics/dunkle/comedy/komos.htm |date=2008-03-24 }}'' in ''Introduction to Greek and Roman Comedy''</ref> The display of a fetishized [[phallus]] was a common feature.<ref>Pickard-Cambridge 1962, 144–62</ref><ref>Reckford 1987, 443–67</ref> In a famous passage in chapter 3.3 of the ''[[Poetics (Aristotle)|Poetics]]'', [[Aristotle]] formulated the hypothesis that the earliest forms of [[comedy]] originated and evolved from "those who lead off the phallic processions", which were still common in many towns at his time.<ref name="Dunkle"/><ref>''Poetics'', 1449a10-13 quotation: {{quotation|Be that as it may, Tragedy - as also Comedy - was at first mere improvisation. The one originated with the authors of the Dithyramb, the other with those of the phallic songs, which are still in use in many of our cities.}}</ref><ref>[[Giuseppe Mastromarco|Mastromarco, Giuseppe]]: (1994) ''Introduzione a Aristofane'' (Sesta edizione: Roma-Bari 2004). {{ISBN|88-420-4448-2}} p.3</ref>
The city of [[Tyrnavos]] in Greece holds an annual Phallus festival, a traditional [[wikt:phallophoric|phallophoric]] event on the first days of [[Lent]].<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/0,1518,553070,00.html ''The Annual Phallus Festival in Greece''], Der Spiegel, English edition, Retrieved on 15-12-08</ref>
In August 2000, to promote a representation of [[Aristophanes]]' ''[[The Clouds]]'', a traditional Greek phallic procession had been organized, with a {{convert|25|ft|m|sing=on}} long phallus paraded by the cast with the accompaniment of [[Balkan music]]; the phallic device was banned by the staff of the [[Edinburgh Festival]]. {{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}
Similar parades of [[Shinto]] origin have long been carried out in [[Japan]]. Although the practice has been mostly eradicated in Japan, a few, such as [[Kawasaki, Kanagawa|Kawasaki]]'s [[Kanamara Matsuri]] and [[Komaki]]'s [[Hōnen Matsuri]] continue to this day.
