{{distinguish|Process theology}}
[[File:Process Church logo.jpg|thumb|right|Logo used by the original Process Church]]
'''The Process Church of the Final Judgment''', commonly known as the '''Process Church''', was a religious group established in London in 1966. Its founders were the British couple Mary Ann MacLean and [[Robert de Grimston]] and it spread across parts of the United Kingdom and United States during the latter 1960s and 1970s.

The Process Church was established by MacLean and de Grimston in London in 1966. The pair had met several years previously, when they were both members of the [[Church of Scientology]]. The duo were ejected from the Church in 1962 and married the following year. They started a Scientology splinter group called Compulsions Analysis, which gained new religious elements and developed into the Process Church. Its members initially lived in a commune in [[Mayfair]] before moving to [[Xtul]] in Mexico's [[Yucatan]] peninsula. They later established a base of operations in the [[United States]] in [[New Orleans]]. Prosecutors investigating the Los Angeles murders committed by the [[Manson Family]] in 1969 suggested that there were links between [[Charles Manson]] and the Process Church. Although no proof of such a connection was ever provided, the allegations damaged the Church's reputation.

In the early 1970s, the sociologist [[William Sims Bainbridge]] studied the group, producing an in-depth account of its activities. In 1974, MacLean and de Grimston separated. The latter tried to continue the group with a small following, but this folded in 1979. MacLean retained the allegiance of the majority of Church members, reforming the group as the '''Foundation Church of the Millennium''' and taking it into an explicitly [[Christianity|Christian]] direction. It was later transformed into the [[Best Friends Animal Society]], based at [[Kanab]], [[Utah]]. 

==Definition==

Various commentators have described the Process Church as a religion,{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=105|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=61}} and it has also been characterised as a [[new religious movement]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}}
There has been some debate as to whether to categorise the Process Church as a form of [[Satanism]] or not; the anthropologist Jean La Fontaine noted that it was "difficult to decide whether it was a truly Satanist organization".{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=105}} The sociologist of religion [[Massimo Introvigne]] included the group in his study of religious Satanism, although added that "its doctrine was not Satanism in the more classical sense of the term".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=337}} He distinguished it from other religious Satanic groups in that it did not have its origins in [[Anton LaVey]]'s California-based [[Church of Satan]],{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=328}} and thus was "born on a different field from other contemporary satanic groups."{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=337}}

==History==

===Foundation: 1963–1966===
The Process Church of the Final Judgement was the creation of Mary Ann Maclean (1931–2005) and Robert De Grimston Moore (b.1935).{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} Born in Shanghai, Moore had served in the [[British Household Cavalry]] from 1954 to 1958.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} Maclean was British but had spent a year in the United States.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} She later claimed that she had had a relationship with the boxer [[Sugar Ray Robinson]], although Robinson's son later refuted this.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} Back in England, from 1959 she worked as a high-end prostitute in London, servicing prominent figures in British business and politics.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} Both Moore and Maclean independently involved themselves with the London branch of the [[Church of Scientology]], and it was here that they met.{{sfnm|1a1=Baddeley|1y=2010|1p=60|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=329}} Maclean worked as an [[Auditing (Scientology)|auditor]] for the Church, although neither became senior figures within the organisation.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} In 1962, they were both declared "[[suppressive persons]]" and expelled from the Church.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} In 1963, the couple married.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}}

Together they set up Compulsions Analysis, a group which utilised both the organisational methods of [[Scientology]] and the ideas of the psychologist [[Alfred Adler]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}} In establishing this company, they were financially assisted by a lawyer friend.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=329}}
Moore distinguished the methods of Compulsions Analysis from Scientology in that it did not claim that its benefits were "infinite", stating that "we are not offering super powers, but a means that people can live on this side more effectively".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=329–330}} In 1966, the regular clients of Compulsions Analysis formed into a new group, The Process, which took on an increasingly religious character.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} In March 1966, twenty-five members of the Process moved into a commune at 2 Balfour Place in [[Mayfair]], an affluent area in the [[West End of London]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} In May, the group decided that they would leave London and relocate to a more remote area.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} On 23 June, around thirty Church members—accompanied by their six Alsatian dogs—moved to [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] in the [[Bahamas]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} From there, they spent the rest of the summer seeking a more permanent location.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}}

In September 1966, the group members moved to [[Mexico City]]. They obtained an old bus and began driving across the [[Yucatan Peninsula]] for a place to settle.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} They found a location known as [[Xtul]]; its name meant "the end" in the [[Mayan language]], and the group took this as a portent that they should settle there.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} They set about establishing a community, although would only remain there for a month. They faced opposition from both locals and from the parents of several Church members, who enlisted [[anti-cult movement|anti-cult]] groups to try and recuperate their children through legal means.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=330–331}} It was while there that the group clarified its hierarchical structure, with the De Grimstons at the top, who were referred to as "the Omega", followed by those regarded as "masters", then "priests", then "prophets", and finally "messengers".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}}{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}}  In late September, a tropical hurricane devastated their settlement, and while some of them elected to stay, the De Grimstons and most of their followers decided to leave.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} The Yucatan experience remained an important part of the Process Church's own mythology.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}} After that point, there would be a crucial division within the group between those who had gone through the Xtul experience and those who did not.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}}

===Establishing a presence in the United States: 1966–1973===

By November 1966, most of the Process members were back in London.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}} Between the end of that year and 1967, the Process began to operate as a church.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}} It became increasingly evangelical and focused on attracting new members.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=60}} It opened a library and an all-night coffee shop known as Satan's Cavern.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}} It also began issuing a magazine, at first titled ''The Common Market'' and later renamed ''The Process''.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}} The Church's activities attracted the interest of a number of celebrities active in the realms of music and cinema, among them [[Marianne Faithfull]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=331}}

In 1967 and 1968, the De Grimstones made various further international travels, spending time in East Asia, the United States, Germany and Italy; in the latter they visited the ruins of [[Thelema Abbey]] on [[Cefalu]], the commune established in the 1920s by British occultist [[Aleister Crowley]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=332}} From late 1968 onward, they began spending most of their time in the United States.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=332}} The Church opened "chapters" in many U.S. cities, the first of which was in [[New Orleans]], where the remaining members of the Xtul colony settled.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=332}} Several European chapters followed, in Munich, Rome, and London.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=332}}
In the early 1970s it opened its largest chapter, in [[Toronto]], Canada.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=334}}
Introvigne thought that at its maximum capacity, the Process Church had "a few hundred active members".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=334}}

====San Francisco and the Charles Manson Murders====

During its existence, the Process Church attracted much publicity.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=105}}
In [[urban myth]], the Process Church came to be associated with [[ritual abuse|ritual murders]], although no evidence of any such connection was ever forthcoming.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=63}} Rumours spread that a number of Alsatians had been [[ritual sacrifice|sacrificed]] around San Francisco, with these actions sometimes being associated with the Process Church, which kept Alsatians as pets. Nothing was ever proved that substantiated any of these rumours.{{sfnm|1a1=Medway|1y=2001|1p=106|2a1=Parfrey|2y=2009|2p=9}}
Baddeley later related that the Process Church "has become legendary, both in the annals of [[History of the hippie movement|hippie history]] and Satanic lore".{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=60}}

{{Quote box
| quote = One could make the argument that due to its extreme views and insular arrogance, The Process Church had itself to blame for the smears and resulting hysteria. But the fallout of this failed suit loomed large in the cult's toning down of its public face, and clamming up in public dialogue about its history.
| source=— Adam Parfrey{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=10}}
| align = left
| width = 25em
}}

Police investigating the [[Manson Family#LaBianca murders|Tate-LaBianca Murders]] which were carried out by members of the [[Manson Family]] suspected a possible connection between the Family's leader [[Charles Manson]] and the Process Church. When they asked Manson if he knew Moore, he responded: "You're looking at him. Moore and I are one and the same".{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=106}} Two members of the Church subsequently visited the district attorney to stress that the group had nothing to do with Manson or his Family.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=107}} The Church then included a brief article on Manson in the 1971 ''Death'' issue of its magazine, in which it included a short essay by Manson himself next to another by the Roman Catholic writer [[Malcolm Muggeridge]].{{sfnm|1a1=Parfrey|1y=2009|1p=12|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=62|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=333}} The inclusion of Manson's piece—gained by interviewing him in prison—was, according to Introvigne, because the De Grimstons "probably wanted to take advantage of the strange popularity the criminal was enjoying in some youth groups".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=333}} 

[[Vincent Bugliosi]], the prosecutor of the Manson trial, later suggested in his book ''[[Helter Skelter (book)|Helter Skelter]]'' that Manson may have borrowed philosophically from the Process Church.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=107}} Introvigne suggested that while Manson had never been a member of the Process Church, he likely knew about it given his base in Haight Ashbury.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=333}} Although no connection between the Process Church and Manson was ever substantiated, the group's reputation was damaged by the association.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=62}} The number of donations received began to decline and Church members sometimes received abuse in public.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=62}} To shift the group's image, its leaders played down their image of black garments and Alsatians and presented a softer interpretation of their four divinities doctrine to limit the Satanic elements.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=334}}

In his 1972 book ''The Family'', [[Ed Sanders]] alleged that Manson had been a member of the Process Church, as evidence citing the fact that Manson once lived in the same road as the Church's San Francisco location.{{sfnm|1a1=Medway|1y=2001|1p=107|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=62|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3pp=332–333}} That year, the Church took legal action against Sanders and his U.S. publisher [[E. P. Dutton]] in the [[District Court of Chicago]]; the allegation was subsequently retracted from future printings of ''The Family''.{{sfnm|1a1=Medway|1y=2001|1p=107|2a1=Parfrey|2y=2009|2p=19|3a1=Baddeley|3y=2010|3p=62|4a1=Introvigne|4y=2016|4p=333}} It also brought legal action with the book's British publisher, although in a British court, the publisher won the case.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=333}}
By the late 1970s—when the Church itself had disbanded—it was common for anti-Satanist literature to allege that Manson was a member of the group and that both were linked to blood sacrifices.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=172}} In his 1974 book ''America Bewitched'', the journalist Daniel Logan cited the Process Church alongside Manson, the Church of Satan, and the British occultist [[Aleister Crowley]].{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=169}} The journalist [[Maury Terry]]—whom Baddeley described as "a sensationalist reporter with a nose for good scare stories"{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=60}}—linked the Process Church to the [[Ordo Templi Orientis]] and claimed both as part of a grand Satanic conspiracy in his 1987 book ''The Ultimate Evil''.{{sfnm|1a1=Medway|1y=2001|1p=114|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=60|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=336}} Claims about the Process Church being linked to a vast Satanic conspiracy and wide range of crimes were also endorsed by members of the [[LaRouche movement]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=336–337}}

A detailed account of the history of and life within the Process Church as told by a participant-observer is contained in [[William Sims Bainbridge|William S. Bainbridge]]'s book ''Satan's Power''. A sociologist, Bainbridge encountered the Process Church in 1970, while he was studying Scientology.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=333}} He joined the Process Church, explaining to its leaders that he wanted to undergo [[participant observation]] in the group as part of his research towards a sociology doctorate.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=333–334}} Bainbridge had conducted several months of fieldwork with the group during the early 1970s, particularly in its Boston branch.{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=10}} His observation took place largely in 1970–71, when he was an active group member, but became episodic between 1972 and 1974.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=334}} In his book, he disguised the names of people to preserve their identities.{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=10}}
Adam Parfrey noted that Bainbridge provided a "more even-handed view" of the Church that that provided by the likes of Sanders and Terry.{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=10}}
Bainbridge's study was later described as "the main source of information" about the group by La Fontaine.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}}

===Breakdown===

The relationship between the De Grimstons grew strained; Robert had begun a relationship with a younger woman, Morgana, who later became his third wife.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=334}} They also disagreed on the direction of the Process Church; Mary Ann believed that they should declare the "Satanic" phase to be over, to be replaced by a "Christian" phase, although Robert disagreed.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=334}} In 1974, the De Grimstons separated.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=334}} Robert took a minority of the group members with him, seeking to continue the Process Church in a manner akin to his original form, although abandoned the project in 1979, when he moved professionally into business.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=336}} 

Most of the Church's members retained their allegiance to Mary Ann.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} She renamed the Church as the Foundation Church of the Millennium, which in 1977 became the Foundation Faith of the Millennium, and in 1980 the Foundation Faith of God; followers generally referred to it simple as "The Foundation".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} The group defined itself as "a Christian church" which required its members to believe in the Trinity, the divinity of Jesus Christ, and his second coming.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} It also promoted a healing ministry which was influenced by [[Pentecostalism]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} Like the Process Church, membership was organised according to a hierarchical system of degrees, and it was led by a nine-member Council of Luminaries.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} Mary Ann's principal collaborator in the group was longstanding Church member Timothy Wyllie. In 1977, he founded a group in New York City called the Unit, which he regarded as being part of the Foundation. Mary Ann disagreed with this move and sued Wyllie, although she lost. The Unit soon disbanded.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} Wyllie then pursued an independent career in the [[New Age]] milieu, with a focus on communicating with extraterrestrials, angels, and dolphins.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}}

In 1982, the Process Church moved its base to [[Utah]], where it established an animal rescue refuge in [[Kanab]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} In 1993, the organisation changed its name to [[Best Friends Animal Society]]; it removed all reference to religious ideas from its statutes.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=335}} In 2004, a feature article in ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'' publicly revealed Best Friends' origins in the Process Church.{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|pp=8–9}} In 2005, Mary Ann died, and the management of her charity was left to her second husband, Gabriel De Peyer, a former Process Church member.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=335–336}} Unverified rumours spread that Mary Ann had been killed by a pack of wild dogs that had escaped her centre.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=336}}

==Teachings and activities==
In the initial phase of the group's beliefs, Moore and Maclean taught there was only one supreme divinity, God, and the focus of the group's activities was to transform those aspects of human nature which defied God.{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}} Many of the group's therapeutic practices or "processes" (hence the name) and concepts were derived from Scientology, including the term "processing".{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}} In these therapy sessions, the group utilised an electronic meter titled the "P-Scope", which was based on the Scientology [[E-meter]].{{sfn|Bainbridge|2017|p=61}}

In 1967, Moore introduced the notion of four divinities to the group's beliefs.{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}} Maclean and Moore were influenced by [[Jungian psychology]], in particular [[Carl Jung]]'s interpretation of the Christian [[Trinity]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=328}} Jung had argued the Trinity concealed a fourth element, hidden in the human [[subconscious]], which was the Devil. He believed that omitting this fourth component of the "Quaternity" resulted in psychological unbalance.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=328}} 

In his study of Satanism, Gareth Medway described the Process Church's beliefs as "a kind of neo-Gnostic theology".{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=106}} The Process Church preached the existence of four gods, who were regarded not as literal entities but as inner realities existing within each human personality.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}} Accordingly, these deities were not worshipped.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}} The names of its deities were drawn from traditional [[Judeo-Christian]] religion.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}} They were known as Jehovah, Lucifer, Satan, and Christ, and were collectively referred to as the "Great Gods of the Universe".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=330}}

The Church stated that "Jehovah is strength. Lucifer is light. Satan is separation. Christ is unification".{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=61}} Each member was instructed to follow the god, or gods, which were best suited to them.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=61}} Each individual was understood as a combination of two of these gods.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}} The Church taught that an individual's personality and relationships could be explained by reference to which gods they manifested.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}} Moore for instance described himself as a blend of Luciferian and Christian traits, while Maclean regarded herself as a combination of Jehovan and Satanic traits.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=61}} None of the deities were considered evil, but "basic patterns of human reality".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=304}} Moore taught the real "devil" was humanity or the "Grey Forces", which were understood as representing the compromise and conformity typical of the masses.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=304}} 

As indicated by the group's name, The Process Church of The Final Judgment, the Church taught a form of [[millennialism]].{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}} According to Process eschatology, the four separate divinities would be unified in the endtimes.{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}} The reconciliation of opposites was seen by Moore in [[Matthew 5:44]], where Christ tells his followers to love their enemies.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=304}}  Moore taught Christ's enemy was Satan, and the "reuniting of the Gods" was achieved through love.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=304}}  

The communal life of the Church members was strictly regulated.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}}
Among group members, sex and the use of drugs and alcohol were strictly rationed, with these practices being regarded as a distraction from spiritual work.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=61}} Unlike other Satanic groups active during the same period, the Process Church did not practice [[magic (paranormal)|magic]].{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=106}}
The Process Church strongly opposed [[vivisection]].{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=63}}

The Church held public rituals similar to Christian practices, such as baptisms, marriages and a weekly gathering titled the Sabbath Assembly.{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}} Baptisms were performed at every elevation of status in the hierarchy of the Church.{{sfn|Lewis|2001|p=215}} The Processeans sang solemn hymns to the four deities during the assemblies.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=304}}  

The group used a swastika-like symbol ("the P-Sign") as its insignia.{{sfn|Bainbridge|2017|p=61}} The symbol had four superimposed P letters, and was also seen as representing the trumpets of the four "Great Gods".{{sfn|Bainbridge|2017|p=61}} The group also used a second symbol, "the Sign of the Union", which featured the letter Alpha inside the letter Omega, representing the intercourse of male Lucifer with female Jehovah.{{sfn|Bainbridge|2017|p=61}} 

==Influence==

[[File:Psychictv-cologne-2004.jpg|thumb|right|Among the musicians and occultists to have been influenced by the Process Church have been [[Genesis P-Orridge]] and the Psychic TV band (pictured)]]

In 1989 and 1990, several former members of the Church attempted to recreate it in [[Round Lake (village), New York|Round Lake]], New York.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=336}} There were also reports of a revival group being based in [[Yorkshire]], England.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=336}}

[[Funkadelic]] included an excerpt from the group's "Process Number Five on Fear" in the liner notes for their seminal album "Maggot Brain".<ref>https://rateyourmusic.com/list/Joci/liner_notes_mania/3/</ref>

In 2009, Adam Parfrey noted that the original Process Church "enjoys cultural influence".{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=7}} 

The [[industrial music]] group [[Skinny Puppy]] released an album titled ''Process'' that contained lyrics espousing anti-vivisection themes.{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=7}} The Process Church's rituals were later adopted and utilised by the band [[Psychic TV]] and the group that formed around it, [[Thee Temple ov Psychick Youth]] (TOPY).{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=7}} Several TOPY members had previously been involved with the Process Church.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=202}} [[Genesis P-Orridge]] worked with longstanding church member Timothy Wyllie to produce a book featuring reproductions of the church's magazines and reminiscences of several members. It was published as ''Love, Sex, Fear, Death: The Inside Story of The Process Church of the Final Judgment'' by Feral House in 2009.{{sfn|Parfrey|2009|p=8}}

Robert de Grimston's writings and the Writ of The Process Church have long outlived the original cult. His 'Brethren Information' (those speeches meant for members of the church at the time) are widely available online<ref>https://processchurchofthefinaljudgment.wordpress.com/free-downloads/</ref>

A detailed discussion of the modern Process Church appeared in [[Disinformation (company)|Disinfo]] in July 2015.<ref>http://disinfo.com/2015/07/process-church-final-judgment-lives/</ref>

