{{short description|Motif and concept found in Buddhism and other Indian religions}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{good article}} [[File:Asian woman making a resolve.jpg|thumb|The motif of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' presumes a natural moral force operating in the world.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|pages=|p=68}}]] '''Sacca-kiriyā''' ([[Pali language|Pāli]]; {{lang-sa|satya-kriya|italic=yes}}, but more often: ''satyādhiṣṭhāna''),{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|p=434}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=149}}{{refn|group=note|Also known as ''{{lang-pi|saccavajja}}'' or ''{{lang-sa|satyavādya}}''; ''{{lang-pi|saccavacana}}'' or ''{{lang-sa|satyavacana}}''; ''satyopavācana'', ''satyarākya'', ''satyavākya'', ''satyavacas'' or ''satyasrāvaṇā''; or simply ''{{lang-pi|sacca}}'' or ''{{lang-sa|satya}}''.{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|p=434}}{{sfn|Brown|1972|p=252}}}} is a solemn declaration of truth, expressed in ritual speech. Most often found in [[Buddhism]], it can be an utterance with regard to one's own virtue, or with regard to a certain fact, followed by a command or resolution. Such a statement is believed to effect a wonder-working power that can benefit oneself and others, depending on the truthfulness of the person making the statement. The ''sacca-kiriyā'' is a motif found in the stories of the Buddhist [[Pali Canon]] and its [[Atthakatha|commentaries]], as well as in post-canonical works such as the [[Milindapanha|Milindapañhā]] and the [[Avadāna]]s. In these stories it is found usually as a blessing, but sometimes as a curse. The motif can also be found in [[Hinduism|Hindu]] and [[Jain]] texts.
The ''sacca-kiriyā'' presumes a moral force of truth that is operating in the world, and is stronger than gods or humans. Although ''sacca-kiriyā'' often refer to characteristics of [[the Buddha]], [[Dharma|the Buddhist teaching]], and the [[Sangha|monastic community]], it can also refer to facts with regard to natural phenomena, such as the sun or the moon. Some scholars believe that the effectiveness of a ''sacca-kiriyā'' as portrayed in stories depends on virtue and good character, whereas other scholars understand the ''sacca-kiriyā'' to be merely about speaking according to facts. Scholars theorize that the ''sacca-kiriyā'' is an ancient belief that precedes Buddhism, but was used in Buddhism as a teaching device to explain [[Buddhist ethics]] and other teachings. The [[principle]]s underlying the ''sacca-kiriyā'' have also been connected with [[Mahatma Gandhi]]'s ideal of [[satyagraha|non-violent resistance]], and many other aspects of Asian culture and religious life.
== Definition == {{Quote box|quote=O great king, is there such a thing in this world as truth, by means of which truth-speakers perform an act of truth?|source=[[Milindapanha|Milindapañhā]] 4.1.42, quoted in Thompson 1998{{sfn|Thompson|1998|p=128}} |align = right |width = 40% | tstyle = text-align:left; |qalign = center |quoted = 1 }} ''Sacca-kiriyā'' is a compound noun that derives from the root verb ''saccikaroti'', meaning 'to bring before one's eyes, see face to face, realize, experience, attain'.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=A Dictionary of the Pali Language|first=Robert Caesar|last=Childers|author-link=Robert Caesar Childers|year=1875|publisher=[[Trübner & Co]]|page=408 |title=Saccakaroti|url=https://static.sirimangalo.org/pdf/childersdictionary.pdf|oclc=922899496 }}</ref> A ''sacca-kiriya'' is a solemn asseveration with regard to the truth, expressed as a ritualized speech act.<ref name="Shaw 2013" />{{sfn|Thompson|1997|p=142}} It is usually a truthful utterance with regard to having performed a certain virtue, followed by a command or resolution,<ref name="Shaw 2013">{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.ahandfulofleaves.org/documents/A%20Companion%20to%20Buddhist%20Philosophy_Emmanuel.pdf|last1=Shaw|first1=Sarah|editor1-last=Emmanuel|editor1-first=Steven M.|encyclopedia=A companion to Buddhist philosophy|title=Character, Disposition, and the Qualities of the ''Arahats'' as a Means of Communicating Buddhist Philosophy in the ''Suttas''|date=2013|publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell]]|isbn=978-0-470-65877-2|page=461}}</ref>{{sfn|Brown|1968|p=171}} called a 'truth-command' (''{{lang-pi|saccādhiṭṭhānaṃ}}'', ''{{lang-sa|satyādiṣṭhāna}}'').{{sfn|Harvey|1993|p=69}}{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|p=432}} The ''sacca-kiriyā'' will usually contain a phrase "By this truth may..." ({{lang-pi|Etena saccavajjena...|italic=yes}}) or "By this power may..." ({{lang-pi|tejasa...|italic=yes}}), followed by the command or wish.{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=66–72, 81}} It is generally made with a specific end in mind, such as to control a spirit, a physical object, or cause something to be done.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|page=68}} Other examples given in the traditional literature are restoring eyesight after blindness, causing other living beings to help,<!--p=68--> causing pregnancy, and causing a sea to retreat.<!--p=69-->{{sfn|Harvey|1993|pages=68–9, 73}}{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|page=430}} Virtues referred to are to have never hurt a living being, having performed generosity,<!--p=68--> kindness, religious devotion and other virtues. The truthfulness in these virtues is considered the "ground" (''{{lang-pi|vatthu}}'') for the realization of the ''sacca-kiriyā'',{{sfn|Harvey|1993|page=69}} but the ground need not be causally related to it.{{sfn|Gómez|2000|page=16}} Sometimes, the ''sacca-kiriyā'' is finished with certain symbolic rituals, such as the pouring of water, bathing and putting on new garments, and so forth.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|page=70}}{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|p=432}} The ''sacca-kiriyā'' is always a formal act.{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|pp=432, 434}} Indologist George Thompson uses the term "[[performative utterance]]" as coined by philosopher [[J. L. Austin]], because the ''sacca-kiriyā'' manages to realize the statement "in the very uttering".{{sfn|Thompson|1998|p=126}}
The Indic ''sacca-kiriyā'' is in its essence very similar to oaths that can be found in ancient [[Indo-European studies|Indo-European literature]].<!--141--> It differs, however, in that the speaker does not necessarily commit to a course of action, but rather expresses a performative utterance,<!--142--> which is immediate and miraculous in nature.<!--143-->{{sfn|Thompson|1998|pp=141-3}}
== Well-known examples == [[File:019 Visit of King Asoka to the Bodhi Tree (33769320382).jpg|alt=Relief depicting King Ashoka visiting the Bodhi Tree|upright=1.5|thumb|Visit of King [[Ashoka]] to the [[Bodhi Tree]].]] There are many examples in literature and in Asian history of people making a ''sacca-kiriyā''. The most well-known is that of the Buddha himself. On the evening of his [[enlightenment (Buddhism)|enlightenment]], as the Buddha is about to attain enlightenment, he is challenged by [[Mara (demon)|Māra]], the Buddhist personification of evil. Māra tries to stop the Buddha from attaining enlightenment by accusing him he has no right to sit on the seat beneath the [[Bodhi Tree|tree of enlightenment]], and challenging him to find a witness to his claim of enlightenment. The [[Bodhisattva#Early and Theravāda Buddhism|Buddha-to-be]] then calls Mother Earth to testify of his [[parami|perfections of virtue]] on the evening of his enlightenment, the earth symbolizing [[sacca|truth and righteousness]]. He refers to the virtues he has practiced for many lifetimes. When the earth confirms the Buddha's claims, Māra retreats.{{sfn|Hara|2009|page=270}}{{sfn|Kariyawasam|2003|pages=590–1}} In another example, the Buddha-to-be places a bowl upon the surface of the water. He declares that if he is to attain [[Buddhahood]] that evening, let the bowl float upwards against the stream, which then happens according to his declaration. In another widely quoted [[Jātaka]] story, a quail is about to see its nest and fellow birds consumed by a forest fire. After the bird makes a statement about the "efficacy of virtue" (''{{lang-pi|sīla-gunṇa}}'') and "efficacy of truth" (''{{lang-pi|sacca-guṇa}}''), and by expanding on the virtues of the [[list of Buddhas|Buddhas in the past]], the fire miraculously retreats.{{sfn|Kariyawasam|2003|pages=590–1}}{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|p=432}}
A legendary example of a ''sacca-kiriyā'' referring to a future act is emperor [[Ashoka]], who vows that by the truth of his intention to support and sustain Buddhism, a dying [[Bodhi Tree]] may be saved, which then happens according to his vow.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|pages=|p=71}}{{sfn|Kariyawasam|2003|page=591}} Another example raised by Indologist [[Richard Gombrich]] is that of the Sri Lankan King [[Dutugamunu|Duṭṭhagāmaṇi]], who used a ''sacca-kiriyā'' in warfare.{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=289}} And more recently, the Buddhist reformer [[Anagarika Dharmapala|Anagārika Dharmapāla]] referred to his good intentions for restoring the pilgrimage site [[Bodh Gaya]] into Buddhist hands, and resolved that by those intentions help would come in this campaign.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|page=71}}
{| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Tradition ! Name text ! Speaker ! Truth referred to in the story ! Statement made |- | [[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Jataka|Sivi Jātaka]] | [[Sivi Kingdom|King Sivi]] | giving his eyes away | "If this saying is true, may the eye be restored!"{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=81–2, 152}} |- | [[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Milindapanha|Milindapañhā]] | the courtesan Bindumatī | freedom from fondness and contempt towards her clients | to cause the great Ganges to flow against the current{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=103–4}} |- | [[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Jataka|Paṇḍara Jātaka]] | a snake king | that an ascetic is deceiving the snake king | "If this saying is true, let your head split into seven pieces!"{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=108}} |- | [[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Jataka|Maccha Jātaka]] | a fish | never having devoured any other fishes | to cause the rain to fall during a drought{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=109}} |- | [[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Jataka|Kañhadipayana Jātaka]] | a mother of a sick child | not having loved her husband | to have the poison removed from her child's body{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=111–2}}{{sfn|Brown|1972|pp=257–8}} |- | [[Mūlasarvāstivāda]] | [[Divyavadana|Divyāvadāna]] | [[Ānanda]], disciple of the Buddha | the [[Triple Gem]] is supreme in the world | to heal and make the body of a maimed man whole again{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=121}}{{sfn|Brown|1972|pp=255–6}} |- | [[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Atthakatha|Commentary]] to the [[Dhammapada]] | Uttarā | not being angry with Sirimā, a courtesan who had a relationship with her husband | "If I cherish anger towards her, may this ghee bum me. If not, may it not burn me."{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=136–8}} |- |[[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Atthakatha|Commentary]] to the [[Dhammapada]]
| Puṇṇa | giving to the monk [[Sāriputta]] without reserve | "May I be a partaker of the [[Dharma#Buddha's teachings|Dhamma]] you have yourself beheld"{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=167}} |-
| [[Theravāda Buddhism]] | [[Jataka|Jātaka]] | [[Gautama Buddha|Prince Siddhattha]] | to become [[enlightenment (Buddhism)|enlightened]] in the future | throwing a hairknot in the air and letting it remain stationed there{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=140}} |- |[[Vedic and Sanskrit literature]] |[[Mahābhārata]] |[[Damayanti]] |her chastity |May her real husband reveal himself to her, and the gods disguising as her husband fail to disguise themselves.{{sfn|Brown|1972|p=255}} |- |[[Jainism]] |[[Parshvanatha|Pārśavanātha Caritra]] |a queen |her husband, the king, has practiced charity in mind |be able to cross a wild river{{sfn|Brown|1972|p=258}} |}
<small>Examples of ''sacca-kiriyā'' in Indic literature</small>
== Motifs and principles == The ''sacca-kiriyā'' is a motif found in the stories of the Buddhist [[Pali Canon]] and its [[Atthakatha|commentaries]], as well as in post-canonical works such as the [[Milindapanha|Milindapañhā]] and the [[Avadāna]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Harvey|first1=Peter|title=An introduction to Buddhism: teachings, history and practices|date=2013|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-85942-4|edition=2nd|url=https://toleratedindividuality.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/an-introduction-to-buddhism-teachings-history-and-practices.pdf|page=238}}</ref> The motif can also be found in Hindu and [[Jain]] texts.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|page=67}}{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|p=432}} The motif of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' presumes a natural moral force operating in the world.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|page=68}} In some stories, as well as in aspirations recorded in inscriptions, mention is also made of [[merit (Buddhism)|merit]] ({{lang-pi|puñña|italic=yes}}; doing good works) as a force behind the miracles that occur.{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|page=430}}<ref name="Worsley 2012">{{cite journal|last1=Worsley|first1=Peter|title=Journeys, Palaces and Landscapes in the Javanese Imaginary. Some Preliminary Comments Based on the Kakawin Sumanasāntaka|journal=Archipel|date=2012|volume=83|issue=1|page=166|doi=10.3406/arch.2012.4342|url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/arch_0044-8613_2012_num_83_1_4342}}</ref> Sometimes the spiritual power of the [[Triple Gem]] (the Buddha, the Dhamma and the Saṅgha), or that of [[deva (Buddhism)|deities]] is also related to it.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|pages=70, 72}}{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|page=430}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=142–3}} Nevertheless, the truth of the statement, its agreement to actual events or qualities, is the main principle that is believed to allow a ''sacca-kiriyā'' to work: in the words of Indologist [[Eugene Watson Burlingame|Eugene Burlingame]], "There is nothing that cannot be accomplished by the Truth. Men, gods, powers of nature, all animate and inanimate things alike obey the Truth."{{sfn|Kariyawasam|2003|page=590}}{{sfn|Burlingame |1917|page=432}} In the Milindapañhā, considered the [[locus classicus]] about ''sacca-kiriyā'',{{sfn|Thompson|1998|p=127}} The protagonist King [[Milinda]] asks how someone's eyesight (referring to a story of [[Sivi Kingdom|King Sivi]]) could be restored by divine means when this seems to contradict Buddhist doctrine. The monk [[Nāgasena]]'s reply is that King Sivi did not receive divine help, nor is there a physical cause for the healing, but he was healed "by truth alone".{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|pp=437–8}}{{sfn|Thompson|1998|p=128}}
Although the ''sacca-kiriyā'' usually refers to a past act, sometimes devotees may refer to a future act which they will perform,<!--Harvey--> or a good intention that has not yet been acted upon.<!--Kong-->{{sfn|Harvey|1993|page=71}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=14}} Sometimes the ''sacca-kiriyā'' refers to a fact in the present, but the expressed wish refers to the future. This form is also known as an 'aspiration' ({{lang-pi|patthanā|italic=yes}}) and usually involves an aim in a future life.{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=179}} Moreover, a ''sacca-kiriyā'' can be performed for another person's benefit, for example to heal another person. In this case, the speaker may refer to the other's person virtue, rather than his own. Devotees performing a ''sacca-kiriyā'' may also refer to a truthful statement about the Triple Gem.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|pages=71–2}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=63–4, 121}} An example of this is the statement that the Buddha is born "for the salvation of all beings".{{sfn|Harvey|1993|pages=71–2}} In the Buddhist text [[Ratana Sutta]] many other examples are given.{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=64}} Lastly, at times, a ''sacca-kiriya'' may refer to the reality of certain natural phenomena, such as the sun or moon, or the characteristics of certain places, or simply a factual statement,{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=11}}{{sfn|Gómez|2000|page=16}} even a failure to do something or a mistake made.{{sfn|Harvey|1993|pp=67, 73}} In general, however, the effectiveness of the utterance depends on the speaker's truthfulness and the religious merit the speaker possesses.{{sfn|Kariyawasam|2003|page=589}}<ref name="Worsley 2012" />
Buddhist tales relate that not only spiritually advanced people can perform a ''sacca-kiriyā'', but also common people<!--Gethin-->, although this is less common in pre-Buddhist [[Vedic]] literature.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gethin|first1=Rupert|authorlink1=Rupert Gethin|editor1-last=Twelftree|editor1-first=Graham H.|editor1-link=Graham Twelftree|title=The Cambridge companion to miracles|date=2011|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=0-521-89986-9|page=229|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NfGlUHU9bCMC}}</ref>{{sfn|Howard|2013|page=56}} Furthermore, in the literature examples exist of people using a ''sacca-kiriyā'' to deceive or curse others, or in other ways act in an anti-social way. Even these people have the power to control the outside environment and people through a ''sacca-kiriyā''.{{sfn|Burlingame |1917|page=431}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=10–1, 153}} Certain people with an immoral reputation in the stories, such as the courtesan Bindumatī, are also depicted as being able to do miracles, based on a truthful statement they make. In the case of the courtesan the truth is that she is "free alike from fawning and contempt" for her clients, regardless of their caste.<!--p=440-->{{sfn|Burlingame |1917|page=440}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=7, 12, 103–4}} Buddhism scholar Luis Gómez argued that the truth of the courtesan was simply that she never denied being a courtesan.{{sfn|Gómez|2000|page=17}}
Scholars are not in agreement what determines the power of the ''sacca-kiriyā''. Judging from the story of courtesan Bindumatī, religion scholar [[Malcolm David Eckel|Malcolm Eckel]] concludes that the ''sacca-kiriyā''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s power is in its underlying intention, not its words.{{sfn|Eckel|2001|page=68}} However, South Asian Studies scholar Choy Fah Kong argues that intention is not the major factor that explains the power of the ''sacca-kiriyā'', but rather whether the statement made agrees with facts.{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=184–5, 188}} In studying examples from Vedic texts, Thompson concludes that the emphasis on self-assertion is a common characteristic in ''sacca-kiriyā'' statements, and that they are not necessarily morally motivated.{{sfn|Thompson|1998|pp=129–30, 145}} Both disagree with Indologist [[William Norman Brown]], who stressed that the ''sacca-kiriyā'' was mostly ethical rather than magical. On the other hand, Indologist [[Heinrich Lüders]] stated that the ''sacca-kiriyā'' is somewhere "in the middle between oath and magic".{{sfn|Thompson|1998|p=140|ps=: "... zwischen Eid und Zauber die Mitte haltend."}}
== Origins == [[File:Religious syms.png|alt=Symbols of all major religions|thumb|According to the Indologist [[Eugene Watson Burlingame|Eugene Burlingame]], the ''sacca-kiriyā'' derives from a belief found everywhere in the world, that truth has an inherent importance and power in it.{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|pp=434–5}}]] According to Burlingame, the ''sacca-kiriyā'' derives from a belief found everywhere in the world, which underlies many forms of religiosity, both of major religions and of [[folk religion]]: the belief that truth has an inherent importance and power in it.<!--pp=434–5--> He adds, however, that at times it may simply be a ''[[deux ex machina]]'' device to facilitate story-telling.<!--p=437-->{{sfn|Burlingame|1917|pp=434–5, 437}}
Indologist William Norman Brown argued that the ''sacca-kiriyā'' is based on "truth of life, personal integrity, truth in one's personal conduct in its totality, truth in acceptance of responsibilities and fulfillment of them".{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=8}}{{sfn|Brown|1972|p=260}} Through this personal integrity, the speaker of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' "can bend the cosmic forces to his will".{{sfn|Brown|1968|p=173}} Brown believed that this interpretation of the ''sacca-kiriya'' dates back as early as the [[Rig Veda]] (1700–1100 BCE). For this argument, Brown referred to an ancient Vedic belief that human beings could derive a power out of truth by fulfilling their [[vrata|duties]] ({{lang-sa|vrata|italic=yes}}) according to the [[ṛta|cosmic order]] ({{lang-sa|ṛta|italic=yes}}). Brown, as well as Indologist [[Heinrich Zimmer]], described the ''sacca-kiriyā'' as such perfect and moral fulfillment of duty,<!--8-10, 101--> referring to examples in Buddhist scripture and the Hindu [[Bhagavadgītā]].<!--103-5-->{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=8–10, 101, 103–5}}{{sfn|Howard|2013|page=52}} This fulfillment implies a high commitment to a virtue or vow and a sense of sacrifice to that end. Zimmer further argued that living one's life in a virtuous way like this, is in itself a ''sacca-kiriyā''.<!--p=53-->{{sfn|Howard|2013|pages=52–3}}
Thompson and Kong reject Brown's theory, however, both arguing that Brown is applying [[anachronism]]s. Kong states that such a belief had not yet developed in Vedic times.<!--92-3--> Thompson takes issue with the moral nature of Brown's theory.{{sfn|Thompson|1998|p=129}} Kong also rejects that the ''sacca-kiriyā'' is a fulfillment of duty, and argues that it is more a statement of fact.<!--107-13--> Kong, as well as Lüders, do concur that as early as the Rig Veda and [[Atharvaveda]], a belief is attested with regard to the efficacy of utterances of truth. Kong does describe the ''sacca-kiriyā'' as a pre-Buddhist "old belief". She does not believe it had much to do with fulfillment of duties, however.<!--139-->{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=10, 31, 92–3, 107–13, 139}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bosch|first=F.D.K.|year=1960|title=Een oudheidkundige benadering van het Brahman-probleem|language=nl|trans-title=An archeological approach to the ''brahman'' problem|journal=Bijdragen tot de Taal-, Land-en Volkenkunde|volume=116|issue=2|jstor=27860228|pp=208–9}}</ref> Drawing from textual analysis of Indic and other ancient [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] sources, Thompson also argues that the ''sacca-kiriyā'' was a pre-Buddhist practice, popular and widespread.{{Sfn|Thompson|1998|p=133}}
Kong theorizes that the idea of ''[[ṛta]]'' as cosmic order should be understood in terms of the original meaning of the word ''ṛta'' as 'truth'. The ancient Indians believed that the world was created through the working-power of speech.<!--pp=40-41, 63--> She also relates the motif of ''sacca-kiriyā'' to the ancient practice of calling out the names of gods<!--p=51--> and requesting something of them.<!--p=53--> The working-power of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' does not lie in its moral intention or fulfillment of duty, but rather whether the utterance agrees with the facts. Furthermore, for the ancient Buddhists, the fact that the Buddha never spoke untruth in itself provided the devotee with miraculous power.<!--..., 194--> She construes that this ancient belief about the power of truthful facts has later been misunderstood by Buddhist commentators, and instead explained as the power of [[jhana|meditative attainment]] ({{lang-pi|jhāna|italic=yes}}), the power of [[metta|loving-kindness]] and the power of [[Śīla|morality]].<!--191-4--> However, she continues, these are not the actual {{em|manifestations}} of truth: only through the manifestation of truth, i.e. the spoken word that corresponds with facts, can a ''sacca-kiriyā'' be accomplished.<!--209-->{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=40–1, 51, 53, 63, 191–4, 209}}
With regard to the ''sacca-kiriyā'' scholars point out that speaking untruth in early [[Buddhist ethics]] was highly condemned, often more so than other vices: in other words, truthful speech was very important to Buddhist ethics.{{sfn|Appleton|2013|pages=31–2}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=169–71}}
== Influence on Asian societies == === Practice in religions from India === [[File:015 Angulimala (9140566999).jpg|thumb|right||[[Angulimala|Aṅgulimāla]] charging to kill the Buddha. ]] In a story about the disciple [[Angulimala|Aṅgulimāla]], he performs a ''sacca-kiriyā'' to help a woman deliver a baby safely. The words recorded in the story have become one of the ''[[paritta]]'' recitations,<ref name="Swearer 2010">{{cite book|last=Swearer|first=D.K.|year=2010|title=The Buddhist World of Southeast Asia|publisher=[[SUNY Press]]|url=http://www.ahandfulofleaves.org/documents/The%20Buddhist%20World%20of%20Southeast%20Asia_Swearer.pdf|isbn=978-1-4384-3251-9|page=253}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Buswell|first1=Robert E. Jr.|author1-link=Robert Buswell Jr.|last2=Lopez|first2=Donald S. Jr.|author2-link=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|encyclopedia=Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism|date=2013|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|isbn=978-0-691-15786-3|url=http://www.daophatngaynay.com/vn/files/file-nen/Princeton_Dictionary_of_Buddhism_890707662.pdf|title=Aṅgulimāla, Paritta, Satyāvacana}}</ref> still chanted today for pregnant women.{{sfn|Appleton|2013|page=141}}{{sfn|Eckel|2001|pages=67–8}} This example shows that the power of truth can still be invoked later, "even when the person who first set the truth in motion has left the scene". The blessing of Aṅgulimāla is believed to be a means to tap into Aṅgulimāla's power. Just like the Aṅgulimāla Sutta, the Ratana Sutta and other ''parittas'' are therefore still chanted today, as part of blessings given on special occasions. These texts will usually contain phrases typical for a truth-command in a ''sacca-kiriyā'', followed by a wish for the listeners.{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=66–72, 81}}
Kong argues that the worship of relics in the early centuries of Buddhist history was based on the principle of ''sacca-kiriyā''. Thus, [[early Buddhism|early Buddhists]], as well as [[Theravada|Theravādins]], believed that a resolve made in front of the relics of an enlightened person could come true. They believed this not because of the invisible presence of the deceased master, but rather because of the truthfulness of the enlightened person: because the relics were of somebody who was believed to be "incapable of speaking false speech", what was said in front of the master's relics had also to come true.<!--285-91-->{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=285–91}} In [[Pure Land Buddhism]], following a similar belief, the power of the vow that [[Amitābha]] Buddha once took to help all [[sentient being (Buddhism)|living beings]] can be invoked again by [[Pure Land Buddhism|Pure Land]] devotees today.{{sfn|Eckel|2001|pages=68–9}}{{sfn|Gómez|2000|pages=15-6}} They can do so by calling Amitābha's name, because "his Name is the Vow".{{sfn|Gómez|2000|page=19}}
[[File:Prathat-offering.jpg|alt=Flower offered in the hand of a Buddha image|right|thumb|When devotees [[Offering (Buddhism)|offer flowers to a Buddha image]], they may make a resolve for enlightenment, as a form of ''sacca-kiriyā''.{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=61–3}}]]Also, the principles of ''sacca-kiriya'' have been connected to the confessions of Buddhist and Jain monks.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Caillat|first=C.|year=2003|title=Gleanings from a Comparative Reading of Early Canonical Buddhist and Jaina Texts|journal=Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies|url=https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/viewFile/8930/2823|page=41|volume=26|issue=1}}</ref> Moreover, the idea of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' may have motivated the aspirations ({{lang-pi|patthanā|italic=yes}}) of ancient Buddhists as found in Buddhist scriptures and [[epigraphical]] findings,<ref>{{cite conference|url=https://globalstudies.gu.se/digitalAssets/1312/1312486_mcdaniel.euroseas.abtsracts.2010.1.pdf|first=Maria|last=Kekki|title=Curses, Truth and the Coming of Maitreya{{nowrap| -}} Lanna Inscriptions as Objects of Power|conference=Magic and Buddhism in Southeast Asia: A Critical Reassessment of the Field|year=2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212002258/https://globalstudies.gu.se/digitalAssets/1312/1312486_mcdaniel.euroseas.abtsracts.2010.1.pdf|archive-date=12 February 2018|deadurl=no}}</ref>{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=167}} and informed devotional practices. For example, when devotees [[offering (Buddhism)|offer flowers to a Buddha image]], they may make a resolve for enlightenment, based on the truth of the [[anicca|impermanence]] of the flowers on the one hand (a natural phenomenon), and based on the power of the accumulated merit on the other hand. Kong adds to that,
{{quote|Though the verse of offering flowers is recited in front of an image of the Buddha, it is not a prayer to the Buddha. Rather, it is an aspiration that is uttered on the basis of the belief in the power of truth utterance.{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=61–3}}}}
Kong concludes that the teachings on the efficacy of [[merit-making]] activities and the [[transfer of merit|transference of such merit]] is "promoted and sustained" by the belief in the ''sacca-kiriyā''.<!--61,205–9, 267--> Other Buddhist teachings such as those about the ''[[parami|pāramis]]'' (virtues to be developed to be a Buddha),<!--Brown--> [[karma (Buddhism)|karma]],<!--204-5--> loving-kindness,<!--136-9--> as well as the spiritual power of the [[Triple Gem]] and the worship of relics among [[Theravada|Theravādins]], have also been explained using the pre-Buddhist belief in ''sacca-kiriyā''.<!--146-->{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=61, 136–9, 146, 204–9, 267}}{{sfn|Brown|1968|pp=175–6}}<ref>{{cite journal| last=Miller|first=B.S.|year=1979|title=On cultivating the immeasurable change of heart: The Buddhist brahma-vihāra formula|journal=Journal of Indian Philosophy|volume=7|issue=2|doi=10.1007/BF00164546|p=211}}</ref> The motif of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' has also affected how the Hindu [[Upaniṣad]]s explain Hindu doctrine. The [[Chāndogya Upaniṣad]], for example, explains the doctrine on the [[atman (Hinduism)|self]] by an example of a ''sacca-kiriyā'' performed by a thief.{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=134–6}}
=== Gandhian philosophy === Scholars have further linked the concept of ''sacca-kiriyā'' to [[Gandhi]]'s ideal of [[satyagraha|non-violent resistance]] ({{lang-sa|satyāgraha|italic=yes}}),<!--p=52--> literally meaning 'strict adherence to truth'.{{sfn|Howard|2013|page=55}}<ref name="Sharma 1987">{{cite journal|last1=Sharma|first1=Arvind|author-link=Arvind Sharma|title=Fearlessness (Abhaya) as a fundamental category in Gandhian thought and practice|journal=South Asia: Journal of South Asian Studies|date=June 1987|volume=10|issue=1|pages=36–7 |doi=10.1080/00856408708723092}}</ref>{{refn|group=note| Historian [[Dietmar Rothermund]] did point out that [[Gandhi]] was not familiar with the term ''sacca-kiriyā''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Der Traditionalismus als Forschungsgegenstand für Historiker und Orientalisten|first=Dietmar|last=Rothermund|author-link=Dietmar Rothermund|page=145|journal=[[Saeculum (journal)|Saeculum]]|volume=40|issue=2|doi=10.7788/saeculum.1989.40.2.142|language=de|trans-title=Traditionalism as an object of research for historians and Orientalists}}</ref>}} ''Satyāgraha'', as Zimmer states, was based on Gandhi's "love of truth and dharma",{{sfn|Howard|2013|page=54}} and scholars argue that [[ahimsa|non-violence]] was Gandhi's ''sacca-kiriyā'', which defined his ''satyāgraha''.{{sfn|Brown|1972|p=267}}{{sfn|Kong|2006|pp=113–4}} Gandhi scholar Veena Howard does point out, however, that Gandhi's ''satyāgraha'' was a political community ideal, and was not limited to the individual as in the accounts of ''sacca-kiriyā''.<!--p=55--> Furthermore, in Gandhi's ''satyāgraha'', the [[Will of God|divine will]] played an important role, whereas in the traditional ''sacca-kiriyā'' this was not the case. Nevertheless, Gandhi's concept of God was abstract and impersonal,<!--p=56--> and with regard to the ''sacca-kiriyā'', religion scholar [[Arvind Sharma]] notes that Gandhi equated God with truth, or even placed truth above God, and morality above the metaphysical.{{sfn|Howard|2013|pages=52, 55–6}}<ref name="Sharma 1987" />
Brown argued that the idea of the '' sacca-kiriyā'' has not only influenced [[Gandhian philosophy]], but has also inspired the national Indian motto ''[[Satyam eva jayate|Satyaṃ eva jayate]]'', meaning 'Truth alone conquers', originating from the [[Mundaka Upanishad|Muṇḍaka Upaniśad]].{{sfn|Brown|1972|p=268}}
=== Other applications === [[File:Xuanzang w.jpg|alt=Painting of Chinese monk walking with a large backpack|thumb|[[Xuanzang]] (602–664 CE)|upright=0.4]] ''Sacca-kiriyās'' may have been used as a device to prove someone's innocence or truthfulness during an [[trial by ordeal|ordeal]], as has been recorded in ancient Indian epics and classical dramas. This involved entering into a fire, and it was believed the innocent would survive the ordeal by the power of their truthfulness, expressed through a ''sacca-kiriyā''.{{sfn|Hara|2009|pages=253–4, 260}} However, in a Jain story relating a fire-ordeal, the accused survives by admitting her wrongdoing, rather than her innocence.{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=12}} Brown did not think that such ordeals were actual ''sacca-kiriyā'', though, as such passages merely teach "the widespread belief that Truth protects the righteous".{{Sfn|Brown|1972|p=267}}
Other applications of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' have also been observed. A ''sacca-kiriyā'' is inscribed at the gateway of the first [[stupa|''stupa'' (monument)]] at [[Sanchi]] with a deterrent statement to the effect that a vandal of the ''stupa'' will be cursed.{{sfn|Kong|2006|p=141}} Also, the Vedic ''[[ṛṣi]]'' poets would usually close their hymns with a ''sacca-kiriyā''.{{sfn|Thompson|1997|p=142}} Furthermore, statements very similar to the ''sacca-kiriyā'' were part of [[brahmodya|religious debates in ancient India]], as the participants of the debate wagered their own lives, should they follow incorrect procedure during the debates. Thus, participants of debates are found to put their lives on the line in this manner in the [[Upanishad|Upaniṣads]], in early Buddhist discourses, and in the accounts of the Chinese pilgrim [[Xuan Zang]] (602–664 CE).<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=The case of the shattered head |first=M. |last=Witzel|editor-first=Inge|editor-last=Wezler|encyclopedia=Studien zur Indologie und Iranistik|year=1987|pages=397, 407–8, 415}}</ref>
The motif of the ''sacca-kiriyā'' continues to feature in South-Asian literature, up until modern times.{{sfn|Brown|1968|p=176}} For example, Asian Studies scholar Keller Kimbrough writes that [[waka (poetry)|18th-century Japanese poems]] contain statements very similar to a ''sacca-kiriya''. Sometimes used to conjure rain and alleviate drought, it was believed that such poetry had to be written with an honest intention to be effective.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kimbrough|first1=R. Keller|jstor=30233775|title=Reading the Miraculous Powers of Japanese Poetry: Spells, Truth Acts, and a Medieval Buddhist Poetics of the Supernatural|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|volume=32|issue=1|year=2005|pages=18–21, 23, 26}}</ref>
Apart from applications in religions that date from India, it has also been suggested some [[Zoroastrianism|Zorastrianist]] texts can be explained as forms of ''sacca-kiriyā''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Malandra|first1=W. W.|title=IE *ṷer- 'speak (The Truth)' in Indo-Iranian|journal=[[Journal of the American Oriental Society]]|date=1975|volume=95|issue=2|page=269|doi=10.2307/600326|jstor=600326}}</ref>
